tIn many aspects the economic activities of a nation may be pursued in much the same way that businesses are operated. -- tThere are two kinds of economic planning. One sort is the planning of final demands and the other sort is the planning of total output -- tPart 3. What Kind of Planning for Canada? -- tWhat can we learn that is of relevance for Canada from the experience of other democratic, industrially advanced nations which have established some form of economic planning organization? -- tPlanning a foreign-controlled economy with a federal constitution is a challenge that can be met only after a drastic revolution has taken place in the minds of the people -- tWe have accepted from Europe the lesson that planning need not imply any antithesis between socialism and free enterprise. -- tLet us at all cost steer clear of the kind of regimentation associated with the centrally directed and planned economy -- tEffective economic planning is more likely to be handicapped in the future by deeply ingrained prejudices about what governments should or should not do than by our inability to determine what correct economic policy should be -- tNo nation can fill the needs of its people and meet its commitments to the world in the twentieth century unless it develops democratic economic planning as a nation -- tWhether we like it or not our planning must recognize the interests of others, particularly the investors abroad who own so much of our industry .... -- tSelected Bibliography -- tBoard of Directors -- tC.I.P.A. Publications0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe papers in this book are written by the speakers, discussion group leaders, and the chairmen of the 9th annual Winter Conference of the Canadian Institute on Public Affairs. The articles suggested a division into three sections. Thus Part 1 contains the articles which centre on the title or ,the compatibility of economic 